 of the ninth to the eleventh centuries may indicate notonly the status, but also the religious and cultural alignment of those who commissioned and made them. Victoria Thompson is Lecturer in the Centre for Nordic Studies at the University of the Highlands and Islands. .  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnglo-SaxonsxFuneral customs and rites. 0aAnglo-SaxonsxSocial life and customs. 0aFuneral rites and ceremonies, MedievalzEngland. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Death & Dying.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon society.  aAnglo-Scandinavian sculpture.  aChronicles.  aConfessional literature.  aCultural history.  aDeath-bed practices.  aFunerary practices.  aGrave monuments.  aHomilies.  aPoetry.  aReligious alignment.  aWills.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615243640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846152436423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846152436/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles